@*
    ── ADR-020 §1: Reactive islands — pattern documentation ────────────────────────────────────────
    Establishes WHEN to use an island vs htmx+Alpine, and documents the mounting convention that all
    three island ports (Take Stock, Intake review, Meal Planner) compose from. (bead plantry-2zvm)
*@

<section class="catalog-section">
    <div class="catalog-section__header">
        <h2 class="catalog-section__heading">Islands — reactive client surfaces (ADR-020)</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
        A <strong>reactive island</strong> is a Preact component tree that mounts on a single DOM
        node, hydrates from server-emitted JSON, and dies on navigation. Islands exist for exactly
        <strong>three enumerated surfaces</strong> (ADR-020 §1) — Take Stock, Intake review, Meal
        Planner — where draft collections, derived aggregates, and out-of-tree interactions have
        defeated the htmx + Alpine model. Everything else stays htmx + Alpine (ADR-005).
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Decision rule — island vs htmx + Alpine:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Use an island</strong> when: the surface has a draft collection whose derived
            aggregates (totals, progress, save-bar counts) must stay in sync after local mutation
            without a server round-trip; or when multiple out-of-tree components need to react to
            the same piece of state; or when htmx + Alpine has already required hand-rolling a
            reactive primitive (manual dirty bookkeeping, <code>_x_dataStack</code> DOM-walks,
            debounced rollup POSTs). These conditions are currently true only on the three surfaces
            named above. Adding a fourth requires meeting the same bar and amending ADR-020.</li>
        <li><strong>Use htmx + Alpine</strong> for everything else — lists, CRUD, detail pages,
            search, filters, settings. A new page does <em>not</em> default to an island.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        <strong>Boundary (ADR-020 §2 / §7):</strong> islands hold UI / draft state only — ephemeral
        field values, open/closed drawers, selected-but-unsaved rows, and derived display values that
        are pure functions of state the island already holds. The server owns every domain concern
        (persistence, fulfillment, cost, unit semantics, validation-as-truth). If an island ever
        computes fulfillment, cost, or any catalog rule client-side, ADR-020 §7's tripwire applies.
    </p>

    <h3 style="font-size: var(--font-size-base); margin: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-2)">Mounting convention</h3>
    <p>All three islands follow the same mounting pattern:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Island source:</strong> one file under
            <code>wwwroot/js/islands/</code> (e.g. <code>take-stock.js</code>), importing from the shared
            runtime (<code>./runtime.js</code>) and helpers (<code>./helpers.js</code>).
            All vendor imports resolve by relative path — no import map.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Hydration payload:</strong> the server emits a
            <code>&lt;script type="application/json" id="..."&gt;</code> element containing the
            typed JSON the island needs for first paint. Read it with
            <code>readHydration(id)</code> from <code>helpers.js</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Antiforgery token:</strong> include <code>@@Html.AntiForgeryToken()</code> on
            the page; the island reads it with <code>readAntiforgeryToken()</code> from
            <code>helpers.js</code>, then passes the token to <code>postJson()</code> for every
            mutation POST.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Mount point:</strong> an empty <code>&lt;div id="..."&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Script:</strong> a <code>&lt;script type="module"&gt;</code> in
            <code>@@section Scripts</code> that imports the island's <code>mount*()</code> export
            and calls it with the root element and the parsed hydration payload.
        </li>
    </ol>

    <pre class="code-sample"><code>@(@"@* At the top of the Razor page — inject IFileVersionProvider and version the entry module
   and helpers.js. The version token is a content hash of the file bytes, so any change to
   the entry module busts the browser cache automatically. *@
@inject Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.ViewFeatures.IFileVersionProvider FileVersionProvider
@{
    var myIslandSrc  = FileVersionProvider.AddFileVersionToPath(ViewContext.HttpContext.Request.PathBase, ""/js/islands/my-island.js"");
    var myHelpersSrc = FileVersionProvider.AddFileVersionToPath(ViewContext.HttpContext.Request.PathBase, ""/js/islands/helpers.js"");
}

@* 1. Hydration payload — typed JSON, server-emitted *@
<script type=""application/json"" id=""my-island-data"">@Html.Raw(Model.IslandJson)</script>

@* 2. Antiforgery token (needed for mutation POSTs) *@
@Html.AntiForgeryToken()

@* 3. Mount point *@
<div id=""my-island-root""></div>

@* 4. Module script in @@section Scripts — use versioned paths from FileVersionProvider *@
@section Scripts {
    <script type=""module"">
        const { mountMyIsland }                   = await import('@Html.Raw(myIslandSrc)');
        const { readHydration, readAntiforgeryToken } = await import('@Html.Raw(myHelpersSrc)');

        const root  = document.getElementById('my-island-root');
        const data  = readHydration('my-island-data');
        const token = readAntiforgeryToken();
        if (root && data) mountMyIsland(root, { ...data, saveUrl: '@Url.Page(""./MyPage"", ""Save"")', token });
    </script>
}")</code></pre>

    <h3 style="font-size: var(--font-size-base); margin: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-2)">Shared modules</h3>
    <p>
        Two shared modules live alongside the islands — import from these instead of
        repeating the boilerplate inline:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <code>islands/runtime.js</code> — re-exports <code>{ h, render, Fragment, html, signal, computed, effect }</code>
            from the vendored Preact + htm + signals files. <code>html</code> is pre-bound
            (<code>htm.bind(h)</code>) so islands import one module, not three.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>islands/helpers.js</code> — exports three functions:
            <code>readHydration(id)</code> (parse the JSON hydration blob),
            <code>readAntiforgeryToken()</code> (read the hidden CSRF input),
            <code>postJson(url, body, token)</code> (fetch + standard island headers:
            <code>Content-Type: application/json</code>,
            <code>RequestVerificationToken</code>,
            <code>X-Requested-With: XMLHttpRequest</code>).
        </li>
    </ul>

    <pre class="code-sample"><code>@(@"// In your island file:
// Note the ?v= query strings on transitive imports — these are the cache-busting
// mechanism for modules not versioned by Razor's FileVersionProvider. Bump the
// integer when the corresponding file changes (plantry-hxkf convention).
import { h, render, html, signal, computed } from './runtime.js?v=1';
// helpers.js is imported directly by the Razor page with FileVersionProvider, so
// no ?v= token is needed here — it gets a content-hash URL automatically.
import { readHydration, readAntiforgeryToken, postJson } from './helpers.js';

// In the mount script:
const data  = readHydration('my-island-data');  // → T | null
const token = readAntiforgeryToken();            // → string (warns if absent)

// Sending a mutation POST:
const resp = await postJson(saveUrl, { items }, token);
if (!resp.ok) { /* handle */ }")</code></pre>

    <h3 style="font-size: var(--font-size-base); margin: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-2)">Production islands</h3>
    <p>
        All three islands are live in production and serve as canonical implementation references.
        Each demonstrates the complete mounting convention end-to-end.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong>Take Stock</strong> — <code>wwwroot/js/islands/take-stock.js</code>.
            Signal-derived dirty/down/delta state, save-bar, per-row reconciliation, the
            <code>postJson</code> round-trip against the production walk-save endpoint.
            Mounted on <code>Pages/Inventory/Walk.cshtml</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Intake review</strong> — <code>wwwroot/js/islands/intake-review.js</code>.
            Full review-form with product search, chip suggestions, row-level edit drawers,
            and commit-bar. Mounted on <code>Pages/Intake/Review.cshtml</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Meal Planner editor</strong> — <code>wwwroot/js/islands/meal-planner.js</code>.
            Modal editor with dish-list, attendee overrides, live rollup, and note-mode.
            Mounted on <code>Pages/MealPlan/Index.cshtml</code>.
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        <strong>No npm, no bundler, no import map</strong> (ADR-020 §6). The file that runs is the
        file you read. Type-checking works in-editor with zero install via <code>jsconfig.json</code>
        + <code>// @@ts-check</code> + JSDoc. The only sanctioned path to a build step is esbuild —
        an amendment to ADR-020, not a silent change.
    </p>
</section>
